Future Plans: Service Type Impact Tuning

Example A — strict SLA
- Deadlines:
  - express: created_at + 3 hours
  - same-day: created_at + 8 hours
  - next-day: created_at + 24 hours
  - scheduled: scheduled_date + scheduled_time (hard deadline)
  - standard: created_at + 48 hours
- Scoring weights:
  - deadline lateness 50%
  - total time 25%
  - distance 15%
  - express-first bias 10%

Example B — cost-first (fuel sensitive)
- Deadlines:
  - express: created_at + 4 hours
  - same-day: created_at + 10 hours
  - next-day: + 24 hours
  - standard: + 72 hours
- Scoring weights:
  - distance 45%
  - total time 25%
  - deadline lateness 20%
  - express-first bias 10%

Example C — express favoritism (premium service)
- Deadlines:
  - express: created_at + 2 hours
  - same-day: + 6 hours
  - next-day: + 20 hours
  - standard: + 48 hours
- Ordering bias:
  - express bookings must appear in first 30% of route positions
- Scoring weights:
  - express-first bias 30%
  - deadline lateness 30%
  - time 25%
  - distance 15%

Example D — balanced + scheduled strict
- Deadlines:
  - scheduled: hard deadline, penalty x2 for lateness
  - express: created_at + 4 hours
  - same-day: + 9 hours
  - next-day: + 24 hours
  - standard: + 48 hours
- Scoring weights:
  - deadline lateness 40%
  - time 30%
  - distance 20%
  - express-first bias 10%

To decide, provide:
1) Deadline offsets for each service_type
2) Scheduled: hard or soft
3) Scoring weights (sum to 100)
4) Any express ordering rule
